Participated in a Department of State tabletop exercise simulating a cyber incident impacting Consular Affairs
Scenario was loosely based on prior OAuth/Graph API abuse and Exchange compromise, with a new initial access vector via a socially engineered senior advisor MDM device
Exercise was divided into two sections with multiple modules, using a branching decision model based on team responses
Teams were organized by function (communications, analysis, incident management, CIO, threat, impact, remediation, engineering)
Each phase required decisions across the incident lifecycle (initial triage, confirmation of malicious activity, and remediation actions)
Scenario dynamically evolved depending on how teams responded to prompts
Gained insight into cross-functional coordination and real-time incident response decision-making
Key takeaway: balancing containment vs. maintaining visibility to avoid alerting threat actors and risking further compromise or data exfiltration
Identified gaps in analyst access to long-term historical data (e.g., inability to query data beyond one year)
Noted limitations in tooling integration, specifically lack of direct querying capability in Databricks using existing Splunk workflows
Overall, teams responded effectively based on the information available during each phase of the exercise
Highlighted importance of incident manager role as a buffer between technical teams and executive leadership
